@node Installation "PostScript PlugIn: Installation"

                                  Installation
                                 --------------

- Read @{" Requirements " link Requirements}

- copy the files from drawer plugins2/ to ArtEffect:plugins2/

- copy postscript-print.guide whereever you can retrieve it.

After the next start of ArtEffect, the menuentry "PostScript..." should be
available in Project-Menu just below "Print...".
There must be an active picture window to call the PostScript-Settings.

@endnode

@node Requirements "PostScript PlugIn: Requirements"

                                  Requirements
                                 --------------

- the only thing you need is ArtEffect2/3

- The PostScript output is using Level 2 operators and will probably not print
  on Level 1 implementations. See @{" Notes " link Notes}

- any kind of need for output of PostScript :)

@endnode

@node Usage "PostScript PlugIn: Usage"

                                     Usage
                                    -------

   When the PlugIn is selected via menu Project/PostScript the settings
   requester pops up. The settings are more or less grouped by subject.

   I tried to give the GUI some "supervising intelligence" (hope it will not
   behave to nerving).
   Mostly done are modechanges to the mode in that a just changed value is
   meaningful. So, don't be astonished :)

   Numberentries out of range will be responsed by a screenbeep.

   The belower mentioned "current picture" is always the picture that was
   selected when the plugin was started. It is not possible to change the
   picture while you are in PostScript-Settings.
   Clicking on a different picturewindow in ArtEffect while the plugin is
   running, may select that window for ArtEffet, but AE doesn't tell the PlugIn
   in a useful way, so this is ignored.

   If you close the settings window via closegadget or execution all settings
   are saved, use 'Cancel' to leave without saving.

   Most items can be selected via ShortCut, just type the underlined letter.
   That's also true for the underlined space :)

   And remember, ArtEffect's numbergadgets are supporting calculations, so if
   you want the double size just use: 2*(oldsize)

       @{" Paperformat " link PaperFormat}
       @{" Imageformat and Placement " link Imageformat}
       @{" PostScript Options " link PostScriptOptions}
       @{" Halftoning " link Halftoning}
       @{" Output " link Output}

@endnode

@node PaperFormat "PostScript PlugIn: PaperFormat"

                                  Paperformat
                                 -------------

   Here you will find a cyclegadget to select some papersizedefaults.

   Alternatively you can enter the papersize by width and height.

   Additional the Border should be set to match the border around the page your
   printer can¥t reach.
   This entry can be negativ to attain some "special effects", e.g.
   postering through prtinting the picture in the double size and align it to
   the left, right (negativ) border.

@endnode

@node Imageformat "PostScript PlugIn: Imageformat"

                           Imageformat and Placement
                          ---------------------------

   Just to mention before:
   Keep in mind, that the orientation of the picture on paper, the decision
   between landscape and portrait is always done automatically.
   No need to bother with.


   FMode: There are three different possibilities

      Autofit    : the picture is fitted to the maximum possible

      Keep Aspect: The sizes and dpis are chained to keep the aspect of the
                   picture

      Custom     : The size of the picture will be as entered

   Width:
   Height:
   DPI X:
   DPI Y:

      These gadgets are just what they seem to be, they let you enter the
      size or dpi directly in fitmodes "Keep Aspect" and "Custom" or shows you
      the results if in fitmode "Autofit".


   Button "Do Autofit/Get DPI from picture":

      The function of the "Do Autofit/Get DPI from picture" button is depending
      on the current fitmode. In "Autofit" it will do an autofitting of the
      current picture (the button is only needed just after the start of the
      plugin, any modechange to "Autofit" or Execution when in "Autofit" will do
      the fitting automatically, this is a feature and done to keep the
      dpi-settings of the last picture printed). In the two other modes the
      button will set the DPI as known to ArtEffect for the current picture.


   Align to:

      Will align the picture on paper to the selected border (remembered to set
      border correctly ?).

@endnode

@node PostScriptOptions "PostScript PlugIn: PostScriptOptions"

                               PostScript Options
                              --------------------


   Colormode: Chooses the outputcolorspace


      RealGray: The color to gray conversion is done with the recommended
                weights to match the human kind of viewing, that should lead to
                better results than MathGray

      MathGray: This is the simple color to gray conversion, done by summing up
                the third of every color gun.

      Color   : Well, color, you know ... Disneyland aso.
                Due to it's nature colored output is bigger, can't be crunched
                very well and takes longer to print on a monochrome printers.


   Maskmode: Play around with the alphachannel of the channel
             mask is also known as stencil :)

      Ingore It      : Picture will be printed as there were no mask at all

      Assume as White: The masked area is outputed as white/papercolor,
                       all transparencies are calculated correctly.
                       So softedges are quiet easy to achieve.

      Crop to it     : Only a rectangular area which encloses all pixels not
                       completly masked is printed.
                       Autofit aso. will work on this area, too.

      Assume and Crop: This is the combination of mask is white and crop.

      Note: Due to some omissions in ArtEffects PlugIn-API, the PlugIn has to
            scan the picture itself completely to get the minimal rectangular
            enclosing every "visible" pixel.
            This may take some time, but if it takes too long an abortable
            progress display should pop up.


   EPS   : If you switch this on, you will get an EPSfile.
           - any given pagesize is ingnored
           - output is always portrait
           - no halftoning settings are included
           - output can not be printed directly ... well you can add a
             'showpage' just before %%EOF and it will do


   Mirror: The picture will be mirrored


   Interpolate : Sets the interpolation switch in PostScript. The
                 interpolation is completly done at your printer, it
                 needs really a lot of time and probably some memory.


   RLE   : Switches on runlengthcompression. Should be on.

           Due to the nature of runlengthcompression and the chunky pixel
           format I use in PostScript only grays are crunchable, so color
           output would not benefit much of it (only if there is a white
           background or something like that) from it.
           However, "Lossy" may help here too.
           Maybe I will do something to change this, but not until I know
           of at least one user of PSP using it on a Color-PostScript-
           Printer :)


   Lossy/Lossyness :  Allow lossy crunching of the image ...
                                                      this option is strange :)

           Runlengthcompression only crunches equal bytes. A sequence of
           n times byte x will result in two bytes telling that byte x has to
           be repeated n times. That¥s easy.

           Lossy allows bytes, which are not the same as its predecessor,
           to equalize to it within the given range.

           So if next byte is in the range of lastbyte ± lossy it is equaled
           to the preceding byte.

           In other words, lossy is a kind of color reduction. It is meant to
           use with low values to equalize e.g. unicolored backgrounds of
           scanned images. Scanned images often show very little dissimilarities
           between pixels of the same (original) color.

           Sequences are restarting at every new line of the image. So it does
           not reduce the colors in a predictable way over the complete picture.

           At least, for most printers out there it save to say that a
           lossyness=1 can not result in any visible change. In the very worst
           case (that is a line with a smooth gradient from one side to the
           other) this will reduce the possible shades of gray to 128. Printers
           that are capable of producing more than 128 shades of gray are very
           rare.

           For natural, scanned pictures and a 600 dpi laserprinter lossyness=5
           should be invisible, I guess :)

           This option was implemented for me to play a little, now you can
           play too :)


   Gamma/Gammaamount: lighten or darken of image.

           The calculation is done by the PostScript interpreter of your
           printer, so it could longer printing time a little, unremarkable
           for me.

           Gammaamount=0, changes nothing

           Gammaamount > 0, lighten

           Gammaamount < 0, darken

           The resulting transferfunction is concatenated with any already
           established (by default, importing program, whoever)
           Due to this, the correction should always be relative to the
           usual output and can be used in EPS-Files, too.
@endnode

@node Halftoning "PostScript PlugIn: Halftoning"

                                   Halftoning
                                  ------------

   First:
      There is no special support for color output yet, color is always done
      with the default screensettings of the printer.
      However the spotfunctions can be set in colormoder, too. This should work.


   SMode: Selects the Halftonemode

      Printer's default: Nothing is changed, no settings about halftoning are in
                         the PostScript output, except Angle, when it differs
                         from 45∞.

      Autocalc: In Autocalc an optimizedπ raster frequency for your printer is
                calculated based on the given output DPI's of your printer and
                the desired numbers of grays you want to have in your output.
                Angle as set in slider Angle. Calculation is done for 45∞, but
                others are allowed too. Angle is always set.

                The settings Printer's DPI and Wanted Nr. of Grays are for this
                calculation only. The resolution of the picture is never reduced
                nor a color reduction is done.

      Custom  : The lpi as set at the frequency slider and the angle as set at
                the angle slider is included in the output.

                The frequency slider is also used to display the currently
                calculated lpi in "Autocalc"-Mode

      Again, in EPS-Mode everything here is ingored.


   Spotfunction:

      You have the choice between 12 different spotfunctions, the spotfunction
      describes the shape of every single rasterspot used for halftoning.

      The following spotfunctions are available and can be selected via the
      cycle-gadget


      PSDot    : The standard spotfunctions normally used in printers. The Shape
                 is a dot for light and dark grays an is mutating to a square
                 for grays of 50% black.

      Dot      : Every spot is a real dot.

      AntiDot  : The negativ version of dot, every spot is a white dot

      Line     : Lines

      Square   : Squares only

      Diamonds : Look like little pyramids

      UFO      : space invasion

      Ring     : Just married

      AntiRing : divorced ?

      ThickRing: 25 Years later

      Cross    : a lot of little crossroads

      Triangle : Triangles, not so straight as Diamond

   All of these (except the first) are mostly (had a very little glimp at
   PageStream3's spotfunctions) invented by me and if there are some
   standardspotfunctions anywhere with the same names is it done by
   accident.
   At least, PSDot is the only one mentioned in Adobe's Postscript Reference
   Manual.

   For high resolution, spotfunctions don't make such big differences, a little
   darker, a little lighter. Dot has more contrast than PSDot, that's nice.

   For low resolution, they can make pictures more interesting.


  πImportant !!

   To get so the called optimal screens let the Wanted Nr. o. Gr. (WG) be a
   number which square root is an integer N, WG = N^2 (N: integer)
   e.g. 4, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81, 100, 121, 144, ... aso.
   And the result of PDPI/N should be an integer, too.
   The angle should be 45∞, but other angles are allowed.

   If these both terms are fullfilled, this calculation matches to the PPDs I
   had a look at. But different can also look quite good.

   HINT: If you lower WG the raster lpi will increase.
         For most laserprinters it is true that higher lpi-values are leading
         to darker printouts. Maybe you should use Gamma to compensate.
         I thought about doing this automagically, but the effect is probably
         too device dependend.

   If you have one of the newer printers, you should think about not changing
   the default halftoning, because they often use more sophisticated raster
   functions (impossible to define in PostScript) with varying pointsizes and
   other tricks and it depends on your printer if it keeps going on like this if
   a parameter of the raster is changed. Maybe it fall back to standard
   function, maybe not.
   I suggest, you just play around a little with this.


@endnode

@node Output "PostScript PlugIn: Output"

                                     Output
                                    --------

   Output to:

      File: Pops up a Filerequester

      The other entrys are a dynamic list of all devices with the potential to
      have a printer hanging on them.
      I wouldn't choose strange devices just for fun, because every device not
      taking over the complete output will let the PSP hang, e.g. a pipe with no
      one on the other end of the tube.

      This list is merely a workaround for all RTpatch (or similar) users.
      With the normal System/ASL-Filerequester it is possible to enter devices
      like them directly and the filerequester don't complain and returns the
      selection to the programm.
      ReqTools' filerequester claims that such a device is a "Bad Directory" and
      doesn't tell the program anything about the users selection.

   EOF:

      En-/Disables the concatenation of the postscript marker %%EOF and
      the EOF itself.
      For some printers (e.g. mine) the EOF is needed to let the printer know
      that it has not to wait any longer for data.
      To fullfill the postscript specs the %%EOF should be there.
      But one may run into problems with EPS-files that are placed with
      a program that don't strip that marker (e.g. PageStream3).
      Some imagesetters may get confused and take that EOF for real. 
      It may be more secure to disable EOF for documents that will be
      given to someone else.

   Be : PSP can tell you a lot of interesting things:

      Quiet  : Psssst!

      Verbose: - Output Formats
               - All values, given, default or calculated.
               - The efficiency of RLE

      Very Verbose:  Additional to the verboselist there is another incredible
                     interesting information calculated (what slows down output
                     a little), called:

                     The Coverage

                     Calculates the coverage of the paper in percent.
                     This calculation is an approximation of the toner
                     consumed by printing the current picture.
                     As you might know, the capacity of the print catridges is
                     normally given in pages with a coverage of 5%.
                     Well, if you print a whole black page (coverage 100%) you
                     "lose" the toner for 20 "normal" pages.

                     This information is not available if Outputmode is Color,
                     the Pageborder is negativ or the current picture has to
                     many pixels (max 2^24-1).
                     Output is slowed down a tiny bit when enabled.

                     In EPS-Mode the coverage of the borderless picture is
                     calculated.

                     The calculation simply takes the grayvalue of a pixel as
                     the percentage of the tonerusage to print it. Weighted to
                     the size of the page it should be near the reality.
                     However, it doesn't compensate for GAMMA setting or any
                     other pictureenhancement/-corrections the printer may
                     perform.

                     It is only perfect for black and white pictures and can be
                     compared to the manufactures datas if the papersize your
                     printer manufacturer used.

                     Take it as the weather forecast of printing :)

                     I invented it, because my 7500 pages catridge capitulated
                     just after 4000 pages actually printed.

@endnode

@node Notes "PostScript PlugIn: Notes"

                                     Notes
                                    -------


 - PSP was written on an Amiga 4000 with Cyberstorm MK1 060 and compiled with
   SAS/C 6.58.

 - The PostScript output has been prooved:

   Mainly with:
                 GhostScript
                 Lexmark Optra S1250, 1200dpi Laserprinter with PS-Emulation

   some files with:

                 Adobe Acrobat Distiller

   It was interesting to see, that Adobe¥s Distiller behaves less conform to the
   PostScript Reference Manual than Lexmark¥s Emulation :)

 - POST.LIBRARY wether old or new (HWGPost) IS INCAPABLE of displaying the
   files produced by PSP.

 - There are processordepending versions because they perform quite different
   on my 68060. Feedback about speed differences would be welcome.

 - This PlugIn has no AREXX-Interface and is not localized nor the documentation
   is available in any other language than english (or whatever this is here).
   That may or may not change in the future.

 - Meanwhile got an updated parallel-driver for my HyperCom3Z.
   And: Woohaa! It sends data with >200KB/s to my printer! 

@endnode

@node History "PostScript PlugIn: History"

                                    History
                                   ---------

V1.1

- Screencalculation of screening choosed by wanted number of grays was wrong.
  You always got twice the number of grays.
  To get the same effect as in older version you have to "want" the double number
  of grays.

- Was not sure about the latest source ... this version should be more ore less
  be like 1.0 again and have the same functions as dt2ps 1.21.

V1.0

- fixed: Due to a little cut'n'paste accident the internal state of the
         postscript-interpreter wasn't restored properly.
         This could lead to strange things such as pictures becoming lighter
         and lighter (or darker) with every print done.

- added: Checkmark EOF

- fixed: Calculation of coverage in mathgray-mode

v0.95

- fixed: a probably umremakable bug in ASCIIenconding

- changed: made some little optimizations in conversions to speed things up
           executable became smaller, too

- changed: graycalculation is even more exact now :) (rounds to nearest now) 


v0.9

- changed: almost everything just added
- added: everything


@endnode

